    <h3>What can be expected</h3>
    <p>
        In a perfect election each signature would contain a unique head shot and device id. And there would be no anomalies. Where there are
        multiple uses of the same device id, it would only be limited to two or three.  When there are more than three uses of a device id,
        the Geographic location info will tell us that it was a nursing home or polling location.  Either way, software would be used
        to digitally inspect the head shots to ensure that they are all different.
    </p><p>
        Where there are clusters of different devices in the same location, the auditing would look at the headshots again to determine if
        they are all unique.
        <h3>About Head shots</h3>
    <p>
        Head shots are more a deterrent in its usefulness than a trait that can be used with absolute certainty.  We think that
        the quality of headshots could be pretty good, but we think the confidence in any attempt at facial recognition is
        not high enough (yet) for anything other than a subjective impression.  We doubt that it could distinguish between
        twins.  It is also possible to use realistic masks for the head shot, but then again, the mask can only be used
        once to theoretically escape detection.  If computer power were unlimited and facial recognition were exact, one could
        ask the computer to find all headshots used more than once in the entire 150 million signatures.  It might already
        be possible to do that. Certainly, on a State by State basis it is doable to digitally review all signatures that fit
        a pattern of ballot harvesting and digitally compare head shots.
    </p><p>
        Nevertheless, the requirement of a real headshot (that is not a photograph of a headshot) is a deterrent.
        A registered voter would certainly want to use their own face for the signature.  Using their face for another
        ballot risks rejection of their ballot.  In addition, lending their face to multiple ballots identifies them as
        attempting to commit a fraud.
    </p><p>
        The proposed system requires a head shot without other identification.  There is no name, address, or any other type
        of identification linked to the head shot.  It is similar to photos taken of everyone at airports or other public places.
    </p><p>
        We also think that head shots of 150 million voter would be invaluable in refining the detection software to
        automatically (digitally) discover duplicate faces in future elections.
